message.content: {"evidence": 20, "testimony": 2}

Testimony 1 claims Sahwit was able to approach and peek through the adjacent workshop door without incident. But Evidence 7 states that door sensors trigger an alarm as soon as an inmate’s bracelet is detected near any workshop door—meaning Sahwit’s approach would have set off an alarm. This directly contradicts his testimony of casually peeking in without raising one.  
{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 1}

Sahwit claims he saw the ring “glimmer” on the victim’s hand (Testimony 6), but according to the autopsy notes the ring was covered by a sheet when the body was first discovered (Evidence 2), making his observation impossible.

{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 6}

Testimony 3 claims the victim “carried a chessboard” from which Simeon’s prints were lifted, but Evidence 14 shows that the board in question matches the one in Mr. Kanis’s cell rather than being on the victim’s person at the time of the crime, directly contradicting Debeste’s statement.  
{"evidence":14, "testimony":3}

Testimony 1 has Kanis adamantly claiming he doesn’t know anyone named Knightley, yet Evidence 14 directly shows Kanis and Knight were playing correspondence chess, proving they had a connection.  
{"evidence": 14, "testimony": 1}

The suspect is claimed to be the only possible perpetrator, yet evidence shows that Sahwit’s broken bracelet rendered him undetectable by the sensors—meaning he too could have been free to commit the crime.

{"evidence": 10, "testimony": 3}

The claim that a dog disposed of the body (Testimony 6) is directly contradicted by the tunnel prints showing bear paw prints (Evidence 19).

{"evidence": 19, "testimony": 6}
{"evidence": 14, "testimony": 5}

The crime scene notes state that the treasure chest was crushed by a ship post, which implies its lid was broken by that impact rather than intentionally by anyone. This directly contradicts Badd’s claim that “Master broke the lid on the treasure chest” to ensure the body would be seen.

{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 2}

Testimony 0 claims that the rock salt lamp was used as the murder weapon, but the crime scene notes (Evidence 2) clearly state that the victim was crushed by a ship post, not the lamp.

{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 0}
{"evidence": 24, "testimony": 1}

Evidence 17 contradicts Testimony 1, as the family photo shows Frost and Gusto meeting outside the contest context.  
{"evidence": 17, "testimony": 1}

Evidence 14 states that Frost’s and Gusto’s semifinal entries “tasted the same,” which implies Frost could bake on par with Gusto; this contradicts testimony 3, in which von Karma claims Frost was a novice at baking.  
{"evidence": 14, "testimony": 3}
{"evidence": 21, "testimony": 4}

Testimony 4 claims that “aside from not cooperating with Sir Frost, the finals weren’t much different from the semifinals,” implying that the flavor characteristics (i.e., tasting the same) carried over from the semifinals to the finals. However, Evidence 13 directly contradicts this by stating that in the finals Frost’s sculptures were “scrumptious” except for the lyre, which was salty—showing a clear variation in taste that wouldn’t align with the semifinals’ uniform taste.

{"evidence": 13, "testimony": 4}

Kay’s assertion that she “can’t remember anything at all” (Testimony 2) directly conflicts with the detail recorded in Evidence 8 that she does remember someone pushing her off the platform.  
{"evidence": 8, "testimony": 2}

Evidence 16 shows that the ringleader (and thus the murderer) was identified by a magenta flower on their chest. Kay Faraday is known to always wear her Yatagarasu pin and has never been seen wearing a magenta flower, directly contradicting Debeste’s claim that Kay is the culprit.  
{"evidence": 16, "testimony": 1}

An explicit contradiction arises between the description of the letter’s location. Evidence 3 states that Kay was carrying the letter herself, whereas Testimony 4 claims Ms. Crane had tucked that very letter away in her own left breast pocket.

{"evidence": 3, "testimony": 4}

The autopsy report (Evidence 11) clearly states that the stab wounds to the chest were inflicted post-mortem and that the victim actually died from a heavy blow to the head, which directly contradicts Franziska’s claim that the candelabrum chest stab killed her (Testimony 1).

{"evidence":11,"testimony":1}

The autopsy report (Evidence 11) states that the chest wounds were inflicted post-mortem, which directly contradicts Franziska’s testimony (Testimony 5) that the victim was stabbed in the chest with the candelabra as the killing blow.

{"evidence": 11, "testimony": 5}

Evidence 17 (the photo showing Rosie Ringer’s assault happening in the storeroom) directly contradicts Testimony 4, which claims she was attacked on the viewing platform.  
{"evidence": 17, "testimony": 4}

The autopsy report (Evidence 11) clearly states the chest wounds were inflicted post‐mortem, directly contradicting the claim that she was stabbed in the heart (which would imply fatal, ante‐mortem wounds) as per Testimony 2.

{"evidence": 11, "testimony": 2}

The candelabrum is described as “what may have been the murder weapon, judging by the wounds to the victim’s chest” (Evidence 9), which directly conflicts with the statement that “the wounds on her chest were postmortem” (Testimony 3).

{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 3}

Evidence 14 indicates that someone was identified by a prominent burn from the recording device in the plushie, implying that the victim’s burn was already known. Testimony 2 states that Blaise “only just learned that she had a burn mark on her hand,” which contradicts Evidence 14’s implication that the burn was used earlier for identification.

{"evidence": 14, "testimony": 2}

Lang’s claim that “there was no one else on the rooftop aside from those two” is refuted by the fact that the side gate’s chain was cut (Evidence 4), proving someone else had access to or left the roof.  
{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 2}

Testimony 3 asserts there was no way off the roof except by elevator, but Evidence 2 reveals a hidden 51st-floor entrance on that same rooftop—an alternate route down.  
{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 3}

Testimony 1 claims that if Shaun had been an accomplice, the gate locks wouldn’t have been a problem—but Evidence 4 shows the side gate’s chain was in fact cut, indicating the “lock problem” wasn’t resolved.  
{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 1}

The clear contradiction lies between Shaun’s claim that the president’s clothes were spotless (testimony 6) and the crime scene notes which describe flecks of yellow debris stuck to his clothing (evidence 5).

{"evidence": 5, "testimony": 6}

Kanis claims he writes letters in braille by hand (Testimony 4), but Evidence 31 shows the correspondence chess diagram—a letter said to be from Kanis—was printed rather than handwritten, directly contradicting his statement.  
{"evidence": 31, "testimony": 4}

Simeon claims he last took the truck (and balloon) out “two days ago” (Testimony 1), yet Evidence 13 shows the blue truck was spotted driving by Edgeworth today, directly contradicting his statement.  
{"evidence": 13, "testimony": 1}

Evidence 19 captures Saint admitting “I was the one who ordered Blaise Debeste to kill Jill Crane,” directly contradicting Simeon’s denial of any instigation in his testimony.

{"evidence": 19, "testimony": 1}

The testimony claiming Simeon was “riding the balloon to the rooftop” cannot be true if the balloon never actually flies but is driven on a truck (Evidence 32).

{"evidence": 32, "testimony": 0}

The victim’s post‐shooting photograph (Evidence 2) clearly shows the bullet wound in his chest from the front. Yet Testimony 3 claims the shot came from “the back.” These directly conflict.  
{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 3}

Testimony 3 claims the Englishman was dining completely alone, but Evidence 6’s photograph of Miss Brett’s handbag on a chair by his table shows she was present at the scene.

{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 3}

Evidence 7 states that the sole drink the victim had was shared with Miss Brett, whereas Testimony 2 claims the victim and Hosonaga were the ones who toasted with the carbonated water, making them mutually exclusive.  
{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 2}

Testimony 1 claims that Brett and the professor “raised our glasses in a toast,” implying they drank something other than water. Evidence 5 (the Medical Report Card) states the victim was “prohibited from eating or drinking anything but water” on the day of the murder, contradicting the idea of toasting with another beverage.  
{"evidence": 5, "testimony": 1}

Beppo claims he only carried four paying passengers that night, but the omnibus evidence (both seating inside and on the roof deck plus the hidden passenger and the defendant himself) shows at least five people were aboard.  
{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 0}

The defendant’s leather gloves show a single bloodstain on the right glove, yet Fairplay insists that both of the attacker’s hands were covered in blood.

{"evidence": 3, "testimony": 0}

The bloodstain on the open skylight frame (Evidence 4) directly contradicts Furst’s claim that “the skylight was shut the entire time” (Testimony 3).

{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 3}

The contradiction arises because Inspector Gregson claimed there was “no one else about but the victim and the accused” (Testimony 1), yet Evidence 10 (Anniversary Bouquet) shows Mrs Beate was present at the scene, having dropped the rose she received as a gift.  

{"evidence": 10, "testimony": 1}

The contradiction lies in Testimony 5, where Patricia claims she saw “four books he dropped at the scene,” versus Evidence 8, which indicates only one book (“The Lion’s Pride”) was found there.

{"evidence": 8, "testimony": 5}

Roly insists the Garridebs are innocent, yet the metal fragment from Mr Garrideb’s broken pipe matches the knife blade, directly implicating him.

{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 0}

The fragment of metal (Evidence 12) shows a piece of knife blade lodged in Mr. Garrideb’s pipe, directly contradicting his claim that even if the murder weapon came from his household, “you’ll have a job proving it” (Testimony 4).

{"evidence":12, "testimony":4}
{"evidence": 13, "testimony": 6}

Graydon insists he’s never dealt with the pawnbroker (testimony 5), yet a redemption ticket issued from Windibank’s was found — the very ticket he claimed Gina stole (evidence 2).  
{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 5}

The bloody fingermark on the redemption ticket belongs to Mr. Mason, not to Graydon, directly contradicting Graydon’s claim that the ticket was stolen from him by Gina.  
{"evidence":4, "testimony":1}
{"evidence": 19, "testimony": 1}

Graydon’s testimony (5) states that he picked up the gun after the girl tossed it, yet Evidence 12 shows the gun was found in Gina’s hand when she was discovered unconscious.  
{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 5}

The Post-Mortem Report (Evidence 0) indicates that only a single wound was identified, whereas Inspector Hosonaga’s testimony (Testimony 4) claims the victim was stabbed multiple times.  
{"evidence": 0, "testimony": 4}

The incriminating photograph (Evidence 5) clearly shows the defendant kneeling over the victim at the moment of the stabbing, implying she removed the knife, directly contradicting Hosonaga’s claim that “there’s no good reason why the defendant would have tried to pull the knife from the victim” (Testimony 2).

{"evidence":5, "testimony":2}

The fountain pen bearing R.M.’s initials (Evidence 3) found in the victim’s hand contradicts Menimemo’s claim that he “never set foot in the hut” (Testimony 5), implying he must have been present to leave behind his pen.  
{"evidence": 3, "testimony": 5}

The fountain pen with a mysterious liquid (Evidence 3) directly challenges Menimemo’s claim that he wouldn’t stab the victim after having already poisoned her (Testimony 1). 

{"evidence": 3, "testimony": 1}

Soseki claims he and Mr. Shamspeare shared a “nice, hot drink” (Testimony 1), but the teacup marked as Mr. Natsume’s has no tea ring, indicating it was never used (Evidence 3).  
{"evidence": 3, "testimony": 1}

The bar of soap with a 2 cm depression shows someone made a non-metal “coin” to run the meter—contradicting the claim that nothing but a proper thruppenny bit can ever fit.

{"evidence": 5, "testimony": 5}

The testimony that Natsume secretly poured poison into Mr Shamspeare’s cup (Testimony 1) is directly contradicted by the discovery of a bottle of strychnine in Miss Green’s possession (Evidence 12).  
{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 1}

Miss Green’s claim that the note “was delivered to me at my address” directly conflicts with the torn envelope piece (Evidence 4) found in Mr Shamspeare’s room that perfectly matches her envelope.  
{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 5}

The torn-off envelope piece found in the victim’s room (Evidence 4) has been proven to fit perfectly with an envelope Miss Green possesses. This directly contradicts her claim that she “doesn’t know anything about it.”

{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 4}

Evidence 7 (Screwdriver found lodged in the machine, not left in the victim’s body) directly contradicts Testimony 5 (Gregson’s claim that the weapon must have stayed in the victim’s body while he was “beamed” through the air).

{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 5}

The screwdriver (Evidence 7) being found inside the kinesis machine despite being metal directly contradicts Harebrayne’s claim that the kinesis cannot transport metal (Testimony 1).

{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 1}

Gotts claims the explosion was a green balloon bursting in the sky (Testimony 3), but the only green fragment recovered— a scorched piece of canvas— was found under the stage (Evidence 4), indicating the blast occurred at ground level rather than aloft.  
{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 3}

Balthazar Lune insists his balloons all have red and blue zigzag stripes (Testimony 4), but the Photograph of the Balloon (Evidence 8) clearly shows a green balloon that exploded.  
{"evidence": 8, "testimony": 4}

Testimony 1 claims the body was beneath the experimentation stage, but Evidence 10 clearly shows the victim’s cage—and thus his body—landed in the Crystal Tower instead of under the stage.  
{"evidence": 10, "testimony": 1}

The bloody handprint on the noticeboard directly contradicts Gossip’s claim that they wiped their bloody hand on the floor.

{"evidence": 13, "testimony": 4}

The contradiction lies between Gossip’s claim of knowing nothing about the noticeboard (testimony 0) and the physical evidence of a bloody handprint on the back of that very noticeboard (evidence 13).  

{"evidence": 13, "testimony": 0}

De Rousseau insists “We ’ad more zan one thousand red-’eaded people assemble in ze park on Lime Street,” yet the Red-Headed League advertisement (Evidence 1) makes no mention of a park gathering—its wording directs red-headed applicants to a bank office, not a Lime Street park, directly contradicting his claim.  
{"evidence": 1, "testimony": 0}

The contradiction lies in Testimony 3 (“And ze next mornin’, we let ’im go.”) versus Evidence 17, which shows de Rousseau and de Rossi still holding the inspector’s warrant card after that “release.” They clearly didn’t return his ID, so they hadn’t truly let him go entirely.

{"evidence": 17, "testimony": 3}

The identification card (Evidence 17) proves that the man was indeed a genuine Scotland Yard inspector, directly contradicting De Rousseau’s statement that “the man who claimed to be an inspector that day… was definitely not this man.”

{"evidence": 17, "testimony": 0}

Evidence 14 and Testimony 4 contradict each other: the Venus Firecracker goes off like a gunshot, meaning a shot sound could have been mistaken for fireworks and thus not heard as a gunshot by the crewman.  
{"evidence": 14, "testimony": 4}

Judge Jigoku insists he “could not have transported the victim’s corpse back to Britain” (Testimony 5), yet the missing crown from Inspector Gregson’s watch turned up in Jigoku’s own cabin on the SS Grouse—proof the body (and its watch) must have been carried aboard.  
{"evidence": 26, "testimony": 5}

The photograph in evidence 10 clearly shows Lord Klint van Zieks with Inspector Gregson, which directly contradicts van Zieks’ claim that there is “no common thread” between himself and Gregson (testimony 3).

{"evidence": 10, "testimony": 3}

Mikotoba’s claim that the victim died from a sword wound (Testimony 1) directly conflicts with the official autopsy report stating death was caused by a close-range bullet (Evidence 11).

{"evidence": 11, "testimony": 1}

The will (The Asogi Papers) explicitly describes itself as “the only weapon I have left,” showing that Genshin Asogi did have something to negotiate with. This contradicts Caidin’s assertion that Asogi “did’nae have nothin’ to bargain with.”

{"evidence": 19, "testimony": 5}

The Asogi Papers (Evidence 19) clearly exist, yet Vigil testifies that they “turned the cell inside out looking for it… to no avail” (Testimony 2), a direct contradiction with the fact that the will was subsequently recovered as evidence.

{"evidence":19,"testimony":2}

Testimony 3 claims there were bloody letters hidden on the victim’s body, but Evidence 4 clearly states the only blood-written messages were on a file (which was then stolen), not on the body.  
{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 3}

Portsman’s claim that Ms. Byrde “snuck into your room using the master key” directly conflicts with the fact that the master key had been stolen (Evidence 6), meaning she could not have possessed or used it.  
{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 0}

One direct contradiction arises between Mr. Portsman’s claim that he had no way to get into the office (“Besides, how, may I ask, do you propose I unlocked your door…?”) and the evidence showing the door had already been unlocked by Ms. Byrde (E6).

{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 2}

Maggey Byrde claims she unlocked Portsman’s office door, but Evidence 6 states her fingerprints weren’t found on the doorknob—directly contradicting Portsman’s Testimony 1 that he “had the girl open my office door.”

{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 1}

The note left by Buddy Faith (evidence 8) states that he brought three pieces of evidence, while Portsman’s testimony #4 claims that only two items were delivered (a gun and a pendant). These two statements cannot both be correct.

{"evidence": 8, "testimony": 4}

The footprints leading away from the elevator are stained with grape juice, not blood, directly contradicting Teneiro’s claim of seeing fresh blood on the murder weapon.

{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 3}

The claim that the murder weapon “is something you stole from Mr. Hicks” directly conflicts with the evidence showing the actual weapon was the Captain Ugo Piggy Bank taken from the in-flight shop, not from Mr. Hicks himself.

{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 1}

Evidence 2 states the body was found inside the elevator on the first‐floor lounge at 6:15 AM, whereas Testimony 3 claims “The body was discovered 15 minutes after that in the lounge,” directly contradicting the elevator location in the crime scene notes.

{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 3}

One clear contradiction is that the crime scene notes place the body inside the elevator (Evidence 2), whereas Franziska’s testimony claims the scene of the crime was in the lounge (Testimony 1).

{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 1}

Evidence 9 (Ms. Meele’s testimony that Mr. Hicks was in his seat at 5 AM) directly contradicts Testimony 1 (that you were waiting in the lounge to beat him to death).  
{"evidence":9,"testimony":1}

Meele’s own “Ms. Meele’s Testimony” (Evidence 9) states that she saw Mr. Hicks in his seat when the plane took off again at 5 AM, yet in her sworn Testimony 3 she claims she was alone in the flight attendants’ room from 5 to 6 AM and could not have been on the cabin floor to witness that.  
{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 3}

Lang’s claim that Officer Meekins “ambushed the victim in this garage and killed him here with his gun!” (Testimony 4) can’t be true, because the revolver used to kill Deacon was stolen from a guard by Deacon himself (Evidence 15).  
{"evidence":15,"testimony":4}

Detective Meekins claims in Testimony 2 that he was out driving the Blue Badgermobile searching for the kidnappers, but Evidence 8 shows the Blue Badgermobile never left the Wild, Wild West area garage (no mud on the tires), directly contradicting his statement.

{"evidence": 8, "testimony": 2}

Oldbag’s testimony that she “saw two men facing each other” directly conflicts with Evidence 9, which states the victim was wearing a fully masking costume at the time of the shooting—there would be no visible “men” to see.  
{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 1}

Lang’s claim that Meekins “shot him from on high” directly conflicts with the forensics. The entry wound is in the lower abdomen and the exit in the shoulder, showing the bullet traveled upward—meaning the shooter was below the victim.  
{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 2}

Lang’s claim that “he drove the Blue Badgermobile here and committed the murder” directly clashes with the fact that the Blue Badgermobile “was parked inside Wild, Wild West area garage the whole time” and showed “no mud” on its tires—meaning it couldn’t have left the mud tracks or been driven to the crime scene.

{"evidence": 8, "testimony": 3}

Lang’s dossier on Colin Devorae (Evidence 11) explicitly states that, despite surveillance, neither he nor his daughter ever showed up. That directly contradicts Lang’s claim in Testimony 2 that “the reunited pair became involved in the house of Amano.”  
{"evidence": 11, "testimony": 2}

Lance claims in Testimony 5 that he used an underground passageway to escape because the door was locked, but the Gatewater Land Pamphlet (Evidence 1) shows no such passage exists under the isolation room or anywhere in the park.  
{"evidence": 1, "testimony": 5}

The dossier on Colin Devorae (Evidence 11) states that Oliver Deacon is right‐handed, yet Paups specifically testifies that the Bad Badger held the gun in his left hand (Testimony 2), a direct contradiction.  
{"evidence": 11, "testimony": 2}

Lance claims the fingerprints on the gun “prove that it was Lolli who killed Oliver” (Testimony 1), but the actual firearm used was the revolver Oliver himself stole from the guard (Evidence 15), meaning the only clear prints on that weapon would belong to Oliver and the guard, not Lolli. 
{"evidence":15, "testimony":1}

The contradiction lies between Evidence 2 (Detective Gumshoe’s testimony that he did not hear any struggle, only a gunshot) and Franziska’s Testimony 3 (that the two struggled, with Rell counterattacking).  

{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 3}

The Crime Scene Notes state Rell was shot from several yards away—contradicting Franziska’s claim they attacked each other simultaneously at close range.

{"evidence": 5, "testimony": 3}

Yatagarasu’s direct involvement in arming the murderer (the knife that transforms from her key) shows she had a clear motive, contradicting Yew’s claim that no one had a motive to kill both men.  
{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 0}

The balloon piece evidence (12) shows the loud "BANG" was just a popped balloon, directly contradicting the Judge's claim of hearing a gunshot (Testimony 4).

{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 4}

Det. Gumshoe claims he never stepped away from the Lobby No. 2 door until he heard a gunshot (Testimony 3), yet his fingerprints left on a hallway bench (Evidence 11) prove he sat down there to eat a Swiss roll, so he must have moved from his post.  
{"evidence":11,"testimony":3}

The Balloon Piece evidence shows that what everyone thought was a gunshot was actually a popped balloon, directly contradicting Badd’s claim that he heard a gunshot right before the trial resumed.  
{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 2}

The key in question isn’t just a simple key—it transforms into the knife that was used to kill Mr. Faraday, directly contradicting Yew’s claim that “you can’t kill anyone with a simple key.”

{"evidence": 16, "testimony": 4}

Testimony 4 claims that “other than her, there was no one else in here with the body,” yet Evidence 29 shows the revolving fireplace wall on Babahl’s side was used—meaning someone else must have entered or exited. This directly contradicts Testimony 4’s assertion of Kay’s solitude. 

{"evidence":29,"testimony":4}

The butterfly-handled knife Shih-na points to isn't the true murder weapon—it has a swapped handle according to the evidence, directly contradicting her claim.

{"evidence": 5, "testimony": 1}

Lang’s testimony insists the Samurai Sword was the bloody murder weapon, but Evidence 16 shows the bloodstained Primidux Statue was actually used to kill DeMasque II.

{"evidence": 16, "testimony": 1}

The contradiction lies between Shih-na’s doubt about Yatagarasu’s existence and the photographic proof of Yatagarasu’s border crossing:

{"evidence": 25, "testimony": 4}

The wire found hidden in Coachen’s office (Evidence 28) directly contradicts Shih-na’s statement that “we found not a single suspicious thing in Mr. Coachen’s office.” (Testimony 4)

{"evidence": 28, "testimony": 4}

Franziska claims there were four passionflowers in bloom at Ambassador Alba’s office, but the physical evidence clearly notes only two large passionflowers.  
{"evidence": 14, "testimony": 5}

The contradiction lies between Lang’s suggestion that the statue was “draped in the Yatagarasu’s clothes, and then shot over here” (Testimony 0) and the Security Footage (Evidence 36) clearly showing the statue being transported in a pushcart instead of being arrowed across borders. 

{"evidence": 36, "testimony": 0}

Evidence 36 (Security Footage showing someone in the Steel Samurai costume crossing into Babahl) directly contradicts Testimony 3 (Alba’s claim that he was in Allebahst the whole time and thus could not have been in Babahl).  
{"evidence": 36, "testimony": 3}

Amb. Alba claims he left the bouquet (with the knife) in the theater, but the commemorative photo shows the murder weapon still in his bouquet.

{"evidence": 35, "testimony": 1}

Alba claims he saw the “Early Summer Rain Jab” on stage (Testimony 3), but Evidence 15 shows the spear used in that scene was bent beforehand, making that move impossible.

{"evidence":15, "testimony":3}
